The '''36.9 ultimatum''' refers to the 1997 ultimatum by then-[[Prime Minister of Norway]], [[Thorbj√∏rn Jagland]], that his government would resign if the [[Norwegian Labour Party]] gained less than 36.9% of the votes (the percentage gained by the [[Norwegian parliamentary election, 1993|Labour Party in 1993]] under [[Gro Harlem Brundtland]]) in the [[Norwegian parliamentary election, 1997|parliamentary election]], no matter what the parliamentary situation would be.
As the Labour Party gained only 35%, Jagland's government resigned, even though the Labour party won the election in the sense that it remained the biggest party and could have continued in government. Jagland's 36.9 ultimatum was subject to much public ridicule in 1997 and subsequent years, as well as strong criticism within his own party.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.proinno-europe.eu/extranet/upload/countryreports/Norway_CR_June2000.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2009-10-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720173437/http://www.proinno-europe.eu/extranet/upload/countryreports/Norway_CR_June2000.pdf |archive-date=2011-07-20 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> When the Labour Party formed a government again in 2000, [[Jens Stoltenberg]] became Prime Minister with Jagland as Foreign Minister; Jens Stoltenberg also succeeded Jagland as leader of the Labour Party in 2002.
