{{Use Australian English|date=June 2018}} {{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}} {{Infobox Political post |border= |post=Solicitor-General of Australia |incumbent=[[Stephen Donaghue]] |image= |incumbentsince=16 January 2017 |style= |appointer=[[Governor-General of Australia|Governor-General]] on the recommendation of the [[Prime Minister of Australia|Prime Minister]] |inaugural=Sir [[Robert Garran]] |formation={{start date|1916|||df=y}} |department=[[Attorney-General's Department (Australia)|Attorney-General's Department]]}} The '''Solicitor-General of Australia''' is the country's second highest-ranking law officer, after the [[Attorney-General for Australia]]. The position is often known as the '''Commonwealth Solicitor-General''' in order to distinguish it from the state solicitors-general. The current officeholder is [[Stephen Donaghue]], who took office on 16 January 2017.
The Commonwealth Solicitor-General gives the [[Government of Australia|Australian federal government]] legal advice and appears in court to represent the Commonwealth's interest in important legal proceedings, particularly in the [[High Court of Australia|High Court]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.directory.gov.au/portfolios/attorney-generals/attorney-generals-department/solicitor-general-0 |title=Solicitor-General |publisher=Australian Government Directory |accessdate=25 August 2018}}</ref> Unlike the attorney-general, the solicitor-general is not a [[Parliament of Australia|member of parliament]].
==History== The office was created in 1916 with the appointment of Sir [[Robert Garran]]. Prior to this, from 1903 to 1913 Sir [[Charles Powers]] had served as the first [[Commonwealth Crown Solicitor]],<ref>{{Australian Dictionary of Biography |first=Colin |last=Forster |title=Powers, Sir Charles (1853‚Äì1939) |id2=powers-sir-charles-8092 |accessdate=9 July 2013 }} </ref><ref>[http://www.hcourt.gov.au/justices/former-justices/former-justices/sir-charles-powers-kcmg Sir Charles Powers KCMG], [[High Court of Australia]]</ref><ref>[http://www.sclqld.org.au/judicial-papers/judicial-profiles/profiles/cpowers Sir Charles Powers], Supreme Court Library Queensland</ref> which later became the [[Australian Government Solicitor]]. Sir Charles Powers was also sometimes referred to as the "Solicitor-General",<ref name=Obit>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12121697 |title=Obituary SIR CHARLES POWERS |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)]] |issue=28,915 |location=Victoria, Australia |date=26 April 1939 |accessdate=25 August 2018 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article42961791 |title=From the States. |newspaper=[[Morning Post (Cairns)]] |volume=15, |issue=44 |location=Queensland, Australia |date=12 June 1903 |accessdate=25 August 2018 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> but the two offices are separate: Powers was succeeded in 1913 as Crown Solicitor by Gordon Castle,<ref>[http://legalopinions.ags.gov.au/opinionauthor/castle-gordon-harwood AGS Legal Opinions ‚Äì CASTLE Gordon Harwood], Attorney-General's Department</ref> whereas the first Solicitor-General, Robert Garran, was not appointed until 1916.<ref>{{Australian Dictionary of Biography |first=Colin |last=Forster |title=Garran, Sir Robert Randolph (1867‚Äì1957) |id2=garran-sir-robert-randolph-410 |accessdate=6 May 2014 }}</ref>
Two solicitors-general have been appointed to the [[High Court of Australia]]: [[Anthony Mason (judge)|Anthony Mason]] in 1972 and [[Stephen Gageler]] in 2012. Gageler is the only person to be directly elevated from the solicitor-generalship to the High Court.
